<h3>Trichromatic Color Theory</h3>
The <b>Trichromatic Color Theory</b> orginates from the work of Thomas Young and Hermann von Helmholtz in the 19th century.
They postulated that the human eye senses light via three types of photoreceptors,
each sensitive to a light of wavelengths within a particular range.

<p>
<div >
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/YoungHelm.jpg">
</div>
@sep
<h3>Cone Cells</h3>
In a currently prevalent scientific model,
color perception is effected by the stimulation of photoreceptor cells on the retina.
One class of such cells are called <b>cone cells</b>,
of which there are three types: <strong>L</strong>, <strong>M</strong>,  and <strong>S</strong>.
Their responsiveness to light of various ranges of wavelengths
peak at approximately:
<ul>
<li>
564 - 580 nm (<strong>L</strong>ong wavelength),
<li>
534 - 545 nm (<strong>M</strong>edium),
<li>
420 - 440 nm (<strong>S</strong>hort),
</ul>
respectively.
<p>
<div class='image'>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1e/Cones_SMJ2_E.svg">
