@sep
In the <b>Opponent Process Model</b>,
signals from the cone cells (and rod cells) go through another layer of processing,
in which calculations based on the relative strengths of the signals
give rise to our perception of hue, saturation/chroma and brightness/lightness.

@sep
In one proposed model, the opponent process filters signals from photoreceptor cells into
three channels of <i>opponent</i> color sensations:
<ul>
<li>
Red-Green (<strong>R-G</strong>)
<li>
Yellow-Blue (<strong>Y-B</strong>)
<li>
Black-White (the <strong>A</strong>chromatic response channel)
</ul>
<p>
<div class='image' style="width:100%">
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8d/Diagram_of_the_opponent_process.png">
</div>
@sep
Experimental data suggest that our perception of red and green is derived from the
<i>difference</i> between the stimuli from the L and M cone cells,
in a manner which is <i>antagonistic</i>.
<p>
@col
This means that, perceptually, one color being <i>more</i> red than another
is equivalent to it being <i>less</i> green, and vice versa.
<p>
@col
Along the same vein,  we cannot <i>psychologically</i> conceive of a color which is both
reddish and greenish.
<p>
Note that, seemingly paradoxically, red and green mix additively to produce yellow,
but most of us do not perceive yellow as being both reddish and greenish.
<p>
On the other hand, we have no problem seeing the color cyan as being both green and blue.
<p>
@col
Similarly, the color sensation of yellow-versus-blue is also processed antagonistically.
No color is perceived as being yellowish and bluish at the same time.
<p>
@col
Moreover, the red-green and yellow-blue channels are independent from each other.
Hence, red and green are both perceived as neither yellow or blue, and
yellow and blue are perceived as neither red or green.
@sep
